<HEADLINE>
<P>
CAPSULE REVIEWS OF AFI FILM FESTIVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following are capsule reviews of a selection of the screenings today and Sunday 
at the American Film Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival at the 
Cineplex Odeon Cenutry Plaza Cinemas. 
</P>
<P>
SATURDAY 
</P>
<P>
'Never on Tuesday' 
</P>
<P>
United States, 1989, 89 minutes 
</P>
<P>
11:10 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 A funny, slick technical exercise, with an all-star Brat Pack guest cast, 
about two girl-crazy teen-agers who crash into a beautiful young model's car in 
the desert. When the model turns out to be a Manhattan-bound lesbian, feminism 
and male hormones are put to a severe test. The most impressive thing about 
writer-director Adam Rifkin is his age: At 20, he's got a good handle on many 
of the pop-movie skills and tricks that would-be sellouts struggle for at 40. 
If he comes on here a bit too much like imitation Robert Zemeckis, salted with 
Ron Howard and John Hughes, at least he has lots of time to grow and develop. 
MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
